 explicitly without using nested loops unnecessarily.\n\nAlternatively: process row-wise with explicit indices. For example:\n\n- Process all rows of m.\n- For each row i:\n   - Create a temporary list by multiplying by the columns of n and summing them.\n\nThis avoids any extra computations since all operations are straightforward in this case.\n\nLet's reimplement `matrixMultiplyNonSequential()` more efficiently, ensuring that we avoid extra loops for efficiency:\n\n```python\ndef matrixMultiplyNonSequential(m, n):\n    \"\"\"Multiply 3x2 (m) and 2x3 (n) matrices efficiently.\"\"\"\n    # The result is a 3x3 matrix C.\n    C = [[0 for _ in range(3)] for __ in range(3)]\n    \n    rows_m = len(m)\n    cols_n = len(n[0]) if rows_m > 0 else 0\n    \n    for row_idx, rows_m in enumerate(m):\n        temp = [0 for col_idx, columns_n in enumerate(n)]\n        # Multiply each element of row from m and column from n\n        for column_idx, (col_element_A, _), ... Hmm, perhaps I should think differently.\n\nWait an example might help. For two matrices m=3x2 and n=2x3:\n\nThe result will be 3x3, where C[i][j] = sum_{k=0 to 1} (m[i][k] * n[k][j])\n\nSo the code: for each i from 0 to len(m)-1, and for each j from 0 to len(n)-1"}], "metadata": {"source": "ollama-deepseek-r1", "loser_idx": 10, "friend_idx": 0, "strategy": "with edge cases and boundary conditions", "tokens": 2089, "ts": "2026-01-23T01:25:12.925510"}}
