ith concurrent requests.append to the app and run fetch on each batch...\n\nWait, this needs a real implementation. Let's proceed step by step.\n\nFirst, define the auth_token endpoint:\n\nauth_url endpoint: POST /api/auth\nThe response returns client_id and username or \"log in on (name|id)\".\n\nLet me outline code steps first before considering all details.\n</think>\n\n```python\n# First, let's implement the authentication endpoint.\n\nauth_url = '/api/auth'\n\ndef auth(request_url):\n    req_max_lims = [3000 / 60]\n    with rate limiter:\n        res_data = requests.post(\n            auth_url,\n            json={\"user\": None, \"method\": 'GET', 'url': request_url}\n        )\n    return res_data.json()\n\n# Secondly, implement batch handling.\n\ndef handle_batch(request_params):\n    req_max_lims = [3000 /60]\n    req_rate = Rlimiter(req_max_lims)\n    batches = []\n\n    def handle_batch_client():\n        if not request_params['batches']:\n            return\n        batch_data = []\n        for batch_part in request_params['batches']:\n            try:\n                res_data = requests.post(\n                    auth_url,\n                    json=batch_part,\n                )\n                chunk = res_data.json()\n                batches.append(chunk)\n                yield chunk\n            except Exception as e:\n                print(f\"Error processing batch {batch_index +1}:\", str(e))\n                raise\n\n    with concurrent requests.append to the app and handle_batch_client loop:\n\nNow, the main GET request function should yield one thread per page.\n\nFirst, define list_users method after auth.\n\nlist_users, which will call auth on any authentication, in batch if that's needed.\n\nWait, since we are about building a POST to /api/users, no.\n\nTherefore, putting it all together:\n\nLet me give the code example for handling the specific request: getting the posts list for the authenticated API.\n\ndef posts(request_id):\n    res_data = auth(request_id)\n    batches = []\n    page_number = 1\n\n    while True:\n        try:\n            req_max_lims = [3000 /60]\n            req_rate = Rlimiter(req_max_lims)\n            requests.append(get_func)\n            res = fetch_request(request_id)\n            # handle the fetched response accordingly.\n\nBut let me structure it as per above:\n\nHere is a way to structure the final code. I will write the Python functions for each step.\n\nFinal API Code Outline:\n\n```python\n# Authentication endpoint\n\nauth_url = '/api/auth'\n\ndef auth(request_url):\n    \"\"\"Accept OAuth token or log in and return client_id.\"\"\"\n    response = fetch_request(request_url)\n    req_max_lims = [3000 / 60]\n    with rate limiter:\n        res_data = requests.post(auth_url, json={\"user\": None, \"method\": 'GET', 'url': request_url})\n        req_max_lims.append(len(res_data.json()))\n        yield response\n\n# Handle batch authentication\ndef handle_batch_auth(request_id):\n    \"\"\"Accept multiple auth tokens in a batch and return client ID.\"\"\"\n    req_max_lims = [3000 / 60]\n    with rate limiter:\n        res_data = request_id\n        while True:\n            with concurrent requests.append to the app and run:\ndef fetch_request(request_url, auth=True):\n    req_max_lims = [3000 / 60]\n    req_rate = Rlimiter(req_max_lims)\n    try:\n        response = None\n    except Exception as e:\n        print(f\"Rate limiting error: {e}\")\n        raise\n\nWait this is too vague.\n\nLet me now provide a functional code outline, handling all these steps. \n\nEach API endpoint should return the right data structure and handle the responses properly. The authentication must be via OAuth token. Each batch of requests uses a separate thread within Python's concurrency framework.\n\nLet's consider using concurrent futures to represent each data request in"}], "metadata": {"source": "ollama-deepseek-r1", "loser_idx": 44, "friend_idx": 4, "strategy": "with adversarial or 